How FTP Works

FTP uses two TCP connections:

1. Control Connection
Port 21
Used for sending commands and receiving responses.
2. Data Connection
Port 20 (Active Mode) or a negotiated port (Passive Mode).
Used to transfer files.


FTP Workflow
+-------------+                     +----------------+
| FTP Client  |                     | FTP Server     |
+-------------+                     +----------------+
       |                                     |
       |------ Connect (Port 21) ----------->|
       |<----- Authentication ---------------|
       |------ File Request ---------------->|
       |<===== File Transfer ===============>|
       |------ Disconnect ------------------>|

Active vs Passive FTP
Active Mode
Client opens the control connection.
Server initiates the data connection back to the client.
Can be blocked by firewalls/NAT.
Passive Mode
Client opens both the control and data connections.
Works better through firewalls and NAT.
Most modern FTP clients use Passive Mode by default.


FTP Commands
Command	   Purpose
USER	     Send username
PASS	     Send password
LIST	     List files
PWD	       Show current directory
CWD	       Change directory
MKD	       Create directory
RMD	       Remove directory
RETR	     Download a file
STOR	     Upload a file
DELE	     Delete a file
QUIT     	 Disconnect


Advantages of FTP
Easy to use.
Supports large file transfers.
Allows remote file management.
Widely supported by many clients and servers.
Disadvantages of FTP
No encryption by default.
Usernames and passwords are sent in plain text.
Not suitable for transferring sensitive data over untrusted networks.
Largely replaced by SFTP and SCP for secure environments.
Linux Commands

Install an FTP client (if needed):

sudo apt update
sudo apt install ftp

Connect to an FTP server:

ftp ftp.example.com

Common FTP client commands:

ls
pwd
cd
get filename
put filename
bye
Secure Alternatives

Copy a file using SCP:

scp file.txt user@server:/home/user/

Copy an entire directory:

scp -r project/ user@server:/home/user/

Transfer files interactively with SFTP:

sftp user@server
